fulltitle: The Pace Report: "Detroit Seeds From The Underground" The Kenny Garrett Interview

description:
Saxophonist Kenny Garrett has just released another important record of his career. "Seeds From The Underground," his second Mack Avenue Records release is Garrett's return to his straight-ahead jazz roots after his last highly successful debut with the label, "Sketches of MD: Live at the Iridium," with the legendary Pharaoh Sanders. "Underground" goes back to Kenny's Detroit, Michigan, in which he wrote a composition in it's honor. He also pays homage to some of the great musical icons that made jazz music what it is today. Compositions like "Du-Wo-Mo" which is a tribute to composer Duke Ellington, and "Haynes Here" in honor of drummer Roy Haynes. Also what makes this disc superb is the killer personnel he has on the disc from pianist Benito Gonzalez and Detroit native drummer Ronald Bruner. Garrett stays true to his stretching out as a saxophonist in the Coltrane and Sanders mode but has kept grounded as a musician that isn't afraid to play what he feels.

Garrett also was part of the Grammy-Award winning Five Peace Band featuring Chick Corea, Christian McBride, John McLaughlin, Brian Blade, and Vinnie Colaiuta.

Currently Kenny is on the road and will be appearing at a club and jazz festival near you. To order "Seeds From The Underground" or to find out his upcoming club dates please visit him on the web at www.kennygarrett.com.
